# Compare + Contrast

Research consistently shows:

# Deep Reading

requires students to:

```text id="m2r6qe"
notice relationships
```

Reading comprehension is NOT:

```text id="r7e4qe"
seeing ideas separately
```

Students learn:

```text id="x5r1qe"
identify similarities
→ identify differences
→ organize information
→ explain relationships
```

This develops:

* analytical thinking
* comprehension
* organization
* vocabulary understanding
* evidence-based reasoning

This becomes:

# Relationship Comparison Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p8r3qe"
compare
=
differences only
```

or:

```text id="u1e9qe"
contrast
=
opinion
```

Some may:

```text id="c4r7qe"
list facts
without comparing
```

Example:

students may compare:

```text id="k9e2qe"
cats
and
dogs
```

by saying:

```text id="n6r5qe"
cats sleep
dogs bark
```

without explaining:

```text id="t2e8qe"
how they are alike
or different
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="q3r9qe"
comparison reasoning
```

For Grade 3:

focus includes:

* similarities
* differences
* signal words
* stories and informational text
* compare/contrast explanations

